up and running. So I get to work, right? I pull down the code, I get the repo, and

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:26.559
I'm so pleased that Travis has left like a fully reproducible report because

00:01:26.559 --> 00:01:30.919
it's a success, right? I get my table and I see my flights delay report. We've got

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:34.360
three airports coming out of the New York City area and some sort of timing

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:38.959
assessment. Let's go back to the email and make sure I can fulfill this request.

00:01:38.959 --> 00:01:42.919
So it says please walk us through the numbers. Sarah doesn't just want me to

00:01:42.919 --> 00:01:46.919
hand off the report and deliver it to her. She wants me to tell the team what

00:01:46.919 --> 00:01:52.239
actually means, like what the numbers mean, all right? So can I do that? Let's

00:01:52.239 --> 00:01:57.160
look at the first cell. 56% of flights, something to do with JFK, something to do

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:04.239
with early. Maybe this means that 56% of flights departing from JFK departed

00:02:04.239 --> 00:02:08.759
early. I talked to Travis, you know, a little bit about this project. I know

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:13.800
there's some nuances, right? Like JFK, like an airport you can depart from, you

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:20.440
can also arrive to. So maybe this means that 56% of flights arriving at JFK

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:25.199
arrived early, and I don't know, and I'm pretty sure this is going to be a big

00:02:25.199 --> 00:02:30.919
deal to the director of flight operations. And the problem here is this

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:36.279
variable name delay category. It's ambiguous. I don't know what it means. And

00:02:36.279 --> 00:02:41.160
so I don't want to bother Travis. He's been sending me pictures of his

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:45.080
vacation. I know he's having a great time on his like Groupon wine country tour,

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:51.360
and so like surely I can figure this out. But in order to figure this out, I'm

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:54.039
really gonna have to dive into the code, right? I'm gonna have to go on some sort

00:02:54.039 --> 00:02:58.240
of journey to understand the source data that it came from and the downstream

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.880
variables that were used to create this report. And this comes back down to the

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:07.800
idea of data stewardship. So as data travels across your organization from

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:11.520
person to person, from report to report, from deliverable deliverable, how do we

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.240
ensure the integrity of that data persists and we know what it actually

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:19.399
means? Like I said, we're gonna start by looking at the code. And we have a

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:23.080
standard data wrangling script here. I'm just highlighting the lines that I want

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:28.039
you to focus on. So what I see here are the two sources of data that I'm

00:03:28.039 --> 00:03:32.679
bringing into this analysis, the flights data and the airports data. This is

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:37.119
actually from the NYC flights 13 package, which is used widely in the R

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:42.399
for Data Science textbook. It's an example of a relational database. And

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:46.679
like I said, I'm gonna have to understand the source data context, right? I can view

00:03:46.679 --> 00:03:52.320
the data in my RStudio data viewer. And to get that data context, I can look at

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:56.679
the help file to see what the variables in that data set actually mean. However,

00:03:56.679 --> 00:04:01.960
most of us don't have data that live in an R package, right? And so we might have

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:06.320
context about our data that lives somewhere else. For me, it lives in an

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:10.559
Excel file, right? And so when I'm working, I have to go to that external Excel

00:04:10.559 --> 00:04:13.880
file and might say something like your data frame name, your variable, and some

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:18.160
sort of description about what that variable actually means. And when you're

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:22.200
working like this, it feels like you're working in two separate tunnels and you

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:26.640
can't see what's happening on the other side, right? You've got your development

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:29.559
environment where you're actually programming, and then you've got your

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:33.440
metadata about like what that data actually means, and you're not talking to

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:39.760
each other simultaneously. So I think the source data context can and should be

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:44.600
embedded in your data. And this is what it looks like in R. It means that when

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:49.359
you look at your data set in R, you're going to see your variable name, and

00:04:49.359 --> 00:04:54.559
underneath, you're going to see your variable label. Have you seen this

00:04:54.559 --> 00:04:59.079
before? Some of you might not have, right? Some of you might be surprised that

00:04:59.079 --> 00:05:03.600
this is actually a feature available to you right now in RStudio. And if you

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:06.600
haven't seen it before, I can tell you a little bit of the history behind it.

00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:12.959
About 25 years ago, we started using R. About 13 years ago, we started using the

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:19.200
RStudio IDE. And about nine years ago, in 2015, was when labels were actually

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:23.679
integrated into the RStudio IDE Data Viewer. So this functionality has been

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:28.679
around for nine years. Now, of course, we didn't come up with this idea of

00:05:28.679 --> 00:05:32.799
variable labels in a vacuum. It exists in other statistical programming

00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:38.679
softwares like SAS, SPSS, and Stata. And since we are at an open source

00:05:38.679 --> 00:05:43.160
conference, some of you might feel like you're marching to the dark side when we

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:47.720
talk about this. However, you know, this is a wonderful feature of these

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:51.279
programming languages, and I feel like we should be more like this. And in fact,

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:57.239
in 2015, when the data labels were introduced to the RStudio IDE Data

00:05:57.239 --> 00:06:02.359
Viewer, was the same year that the Haven package came out, which enables you to

00:06:02.359 --> 00:06:08.200
import SAS, SPSS, and Stata datasets into RStudio and retain their metadata in the

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:12.880
form of variable and value labels. Now, I'm not here to talk to you about, like,

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:17.359
what if you already have labeled data and you want to work with it in R. I'm here

00:06:17.359 --> 00:06:21.640
to talk to you about you have data and you want to label it. So how do we do

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:26.760
that? I like to use a function in the labeled package called set variable

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:30.480
labels, and you're just going to iterate over the variables with their

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:34.760
descriptions in order to do this. If you want to read more about it, you can read

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:40.320
my blog post, The Case for Variable Labels in R. You don't actually have to

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:44.799
use the labeled package to do this. You can do this entirely in base R because a

00:06:44.799 --> 00:06:49.959
label is essentially an attribute on a column in your data frame. It's a way of

00:06:49.959 --> 00:06:54.880
storing metadata attached to an object. So you can read more about attributes in

00:06:54.880 --> 00:07:01.079
Advanced R. And so just so you can see the difference between the two, on the

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:06.720
left-hand side we are seeing unlabeled data, where all you see are your

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:10.779
variable names, but on the right-hand side, and my labeled data is going to be

00:07:10.779 --> 00:07:14.500
denoted, underscore labeled, you're going to see your variable names with the

00:07:14.500 --> 00:07:20.100
very important context of what that data means embedded in your data. And you

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:24.339
can imagine I have feelings about this, right? Like I find having the data

00:07:24.339 --> 00:07:28.700
context at my fingertips in my programming environment incredibly

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:32.940
empowering. Allows me to get to my up to speed with my data so much faster.

00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:38.820
There's other ways you can actually view the labeled labels of your data. So for

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:42.540
example, we already mentioned it's an attribute of columns on your data frame,

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:45.899
so you can see the values of those attributes when you call the store

00:07:45.899 --> 00:07:52.540
command as well. So far we've only talked about our source data context, but what

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:55.540
we do in data science is we create new variables. So we're going to have some

00:07:55.540 --> 00:07:59.459
downstream context. And like I said, I have to go on some journey to figure

00:07:59.459 --> 00:08:03.700
this out. So just highlighting some quick points here, we're looking at something

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:07.339
to do with an origin airport, and we're looking at some variable called

00:08:07.339 --> 00:08:12.140
departure delay. So I can deduce that delay category represents departure

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:16.980
timing by origin airport. And now that I know that, when I do my data wrangling

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:21.820
script, I should set my variable labels so that I know the context of what my

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:28.540
new variables actually mean. And I think as people who work with data, we've all

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:32.659
felt these competing forces, right? On one hand, we want these really short

00:08:32.659 --> 00:08:37.580
succinct variable names so that we can write our code really fast. And on the

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:40.900
other hand, we need some descriptive text so that we can understand the context of

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:46.739
what our data means, and we can have it both ways to prop up our data. And so I

00:08:46.739 --> 00:08:51.700
truly believe that assigning variable labels encourages a disciplined practice

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:56.619
of creating explicit and succinct variable descriptions and ensures that

00:08:56.619 --> 00:09:01.859
data context lives with the data. You should be doing this. It's going to help

00:09:01.859 --> 00:09:07.659
current you, future you, colleagues. It's going to help peer review processes. Can

00:09:07.659 --> 00:09:10.260
you imagine? You get to read code and actually know what it's supposed to do.

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:16.900
And it's going to help with the creation of reusable data assets. And it comes

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:20.460
back down to this idea of data stewardship. When you're pulling data

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:24.539
together, it's just the beginning of a journey. You don't know exactly where

00:09:24.539 --> 00:09:28.460
it's going to go in your organization, who it's going to go to, or what report

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:31.539
it's going to land in. You don't know what's around the corner for that data.

00:09:31.539 --> 00:09:36.500
And to be fair, data stewardship, the concept of it, it's a little bit broader

00:09:36.619 --> 00:09:40.179
than what I'm talking about today. Really, it's the practice of ensuring that data

00:09:40.179 --> 00:09:45.659
assets are accessible, secure, trustworthy, and usable. And today, I want

00:09:45.659 --> 00:09:52.780
you to think about these trustworthy and usable aspects. Some of you might be with

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:55.940
me right now. Some of you might be on board. Yes, Shannon, I hear you. Variable

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:59.619
labels, it's the way to go. And some of you might be feeling a little bit like

00:09:59.619 --> 00:10:04.260
this. Shannon, I hear the medicine that you're trying to give me, and I'm just

00:10:04.299 --> 00:10:11.460
not ready to swallow it. So let me sugarcoat it for you. There's some

00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:16.020
applications. Because now that we have metadata embedded in our data that we

00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:18.780
can access in our programming environment, we can do very cool

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:24.099
programming things with it at our fingertips. One example is a data

00:10:24.099 --> 00:10:28.700
dictionary. Suppose for your entire relational database, you have some sort

00:10:28.700 --> 00:10:34.700
of schema, maybe it goes into a list. You can iterate over that list to create a

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:38.219
dictionary of your entire database right there in your programming environment.

00:10:38.219 --> 00:10:42.780
And when you look at that dictionary, it's easy to scroll through, it's easy to

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:48.299
search, and figure out what is in your data schema. And so, for example, I can

00:10:48.299 --> 00:10:56.940
search on the word year. There we go. And it's going to pop up everywhere that it

00:10:56.940 --> 00:11:03.219
applies in my data set. It's a huge way to get up and running faster. What about

00:11:03.219 --> 00:11:10.020
ggplot figures? So here, I am taking data that is indeed already labeled, and I'm

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:15.140
creating a ggplot. And you can see the default for the ggplot is just to show

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:19.340
your variable names, right? On the x-axis, you see the name, on the legend, you see

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:25.059
delay category. Instead, we apply the function easy labs from ggeasy. It will

00:11:25.059 --> 00:11:30.500
automatically substitute in those variable labels into your plot for you.

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:36.979
What about tabling? So here, I'm starting with data that's actually not labeled.

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:42.820
And I'm using the GT summary table with a table summary function in order to

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:48.020
create a table. And you can see when you have unlabeled data, you're going to see

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:53.820
the variable name. However, if instead you actually had labeled data and use that

00:11:53.820 --> 00:11:58.659
same table summary function, GT summary is going to use your variable label

00:11:58.659 --> 00:12:04.739
instead of your variable name in the output. And GT summary does leverage GT,

00:12:04.739 --> 00:12:09.419
and GT has the same behavior. And if Travis had just done that from the

00:12:09.419 --> 00:12:14.260
beginning, I wouldn't have had to go on my journey, and I wouldn't have had to even

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:20.619
think about bothering him while he was on vacation. And what does this look like in

00:12:20.619 --> 00:12:27.219
practice? I told you, I work on clinical trials, right? And the NYC flights

00:12:27.219 --> 00:12:32.179
data frame or relational database that we've talked about, it's got five data

00:12:32.179 --> 00:12:42.179
frames and 53 variables. One clinical trial that I work on has 90 data frames

00:12:42.179 --> 00:12:52.979
and 1,400 variables. That's one. We have 15 active trials in our portfolio.

00:12:52.979 --> 00:12:57.700
So I am constantly diving in and out of data all day long, and I have to get up to

00:12:57.700 --> 00:13:05.099
speed quickly in order to be effective at my job. And that was just the source data,

00:13:05.099 --> 00:13:09.419
right? Because then we take that source data, and we tinker with it, and we combine

00:13:09.419 --> 00:13:13.700
it, and we enjoin it, and we rearrange it, and we create more data. That's our

00:13:13.700 --> 00:13:18.419
downstream data. And so that same trial, our downstream data also looks like an

00:13:18.419 --> 00:13:26.460
additional 50 data frames and 700 variables for our various reporting needs.

00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:30.700
And no one wants to write out 700 lines of code to label variables, I promise you

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:36.059
that. So how do we do it? Here's our strategy. I'm not saying it's a strategy

00:13:36.059 --> 00:13:39.179
you should be using or anything like that. I just want to let you know how we do it.

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:45.580
And it's pretty low-tech. So we start off by maintaining a CSV with metadata.

00:13:45.580 --> 00:13:48.859
This was a decision so that we can look at the diff when we go to GitHub and see

00:13:48.859 --> 00:13:54.299
what variables were added and deleted and then changed over time. And then we take

00:13:54.299 --> 00:14:00.059
that CSV, we do our standard data wrangling operation, and then we can use an

00:14:00.059 --> 00:14:04.299
internal function called setDerivedVariableLabels from the croquet package,

00:14:04.299 --> 00:14:08.140
which is open source if you want to check it out. It's called derived variable

00:14:08.140 --> 00:14:12.619
labels because in our industry downstream variables are called derived.

00:14:12.619 --> 00:14:16.780
And then you have it. You're going to have a data frame that has applied all of your

00:14:16.780 --> 00:14:22.140
variable labels. What if you want to do it on a bigger scale? Maybe a list of data

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:26.539
frames? It's going to be the same strategy. You're still going to do the hard work

00:14:26.539 --> 00:14:31.179
maintaining that CSV with your precious metadata. And you're still going to just

00:14:31.179 --> 00:14:34.619
apply that custom function for bulk label assignment. You're just going to do it in

00:14:34.619 --> 00:14:39.979
iterative framework. So all of your 700 variables can be labeled at one time.

00:14:42.539 --> 00:14:50.859
So let's wrap up. This is the process of data science, right? And every single

00:14:50.859 --> 00:14:55.739
place in this process, we have to understand the context of our data in order to be

00:14:55.739 --> 00:15:00.539
effective data scientists. So I think we can make this easier for us if we

00:15:00.539 --> 00:15:06.299
actually embed our context in our data. And there's a whole suite of packages that

00:15:06.299 --> 00:15:09.900
help you with this process, right? We have packages for importing label data,

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:14.140
for assigning labels, for working with labels, and for doing really cool things with those labels.

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:19.099
And this is great. And I think there's a lot of opportunity to grow here. I'd love to see

00:15:19.099 --> 00:15:24.059
other packages come up with cool ways to leverage their metadata or their variable labels.

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:29.739
And so, so far, I've only talked to you about this narrow world view.

00:15:29.739 --> 00:15:35.500
What if you're programming in R and the RStudio IDE and you're working with R data?

00:15:36.059 --> 00:15:42.380
And I realize there's a bigger world out there, a bigger universe, right? Like, we use different

00:15:42.380 --> 00:15:46.780
open source programming languages. We use different development environments. And we

00:15:46.780 --> 00:15:52.219
certainly ingest data from and save data to and connect with data in different ways, right?

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:58.380
And if you're wondering how this looks for you, for your specific use case, I'm sorry,

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:02.539
I probably don't know. But I do have some questions for you.

00:16:05.419 --> 00:16:11.979
Do you have sufficient metadata to facilitate reusable data assets? And if you don't,

00:16:11.979 --> 00:16:14.539
I think you should stop everything you're doing and come up with a plan.

00:16:16.219 --> 00:16:22.059
And can you access and leverage the metadata in your programming environment? If you don't know,

00:16:22.059 --> 00:16:27.260
I encourage you to figure it out. And if you know the answer is no, I encourage you to talk

00:16:27.260 --> 00:16:32.299
to the people who build your tools and make your case for your vision of an awesome future where

00:16:32.299 --> 00:16:36.700
you can really take advantage of this to be a better data scientist and work more effectively.

00:16:39.340 --> 00:16:46.299
Speaking of, Positron has an open issue to display column labels in the Data Explorer.

00:16:46.299 --> 00:16:50.059
I invite you to follow along or contribute your thoughts and suggestions to the issue.

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:56.940
I have some more resources for you. And I want to say thank you to the many individuals who have

00:16:56.940 --> 00:17:01.900
helped me develop this talk. If you want to get in touch with me, my contact information is on my

00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:08.140
website, piping hot data. These slides are on my GitHub repo. Context is king. This is my awesome

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:12.619
data science team. We love using variable labels and Travis did consent for me to use his name.

00:17:12.619 --> 00:17:14.619
Thank you.

00:17:14.939 --> 00:17:29.579
Thank you so much, Shannon. I have to admit I do not use variable labels, but I will be trying them

00:17:29.579 --> 00:17:35.979
out next time I have the opportunity to. We have a few questions from our virtual audience.

00:17:37.339 --> 00:17:41.420
Are there strategies to handle the way that label attributes are dropped by some data frame

00:17:41.420 --> 00:17:48.619
operations? Yeah. Relabel. Relabel. Yeah. Okay.

00:17:53.819 --> 00:17:58.060
What kind of change management towards team norms was necessary to make this standard practice?

00:17:59.900 --> 00:18:04.060
I mean, we really had to think hard about our templating structure for our projects.

00:18:04.780 --> 00:18:08.219
And once we landed on a solution that worked for everyone, it was pretty easy.

00:18:09.099 --> 00:18:17.819
Awesome. Can you speak to the pros of labeling as opposed to more explicit column naming?

00:18:19.739 --> 00:18:24.219
I don't think you can really cram all the context that you need in a single column name.

